# Revised master strategy

## Principle

Split the Google layout track into two clearly separated assets:

* **`GoogleLayoutLegacy`**, frozen, stable, reference implementation
* **`GoogleLayout`**, active improvement implementation

## Why this is the right decision

This removes the biggest source of risk from the earlier effort:

* you were improving and destabilizing the same layout at once
* once regressions appeared, you lost the clean reference point
* debugging became ambiguous because “baseline” and “experimental” were mixed

With the revised structure:

* `google_legacy` becomes the known-good fallback
* `google` becomes the controlled improvement track
* every change can be compared against a stable operational reference

This is the correct engineering pattern for UI migration.

---

# Core rules for the repo

## Rule 1

`GoogleLayoutLegacy` is frozen after creation.

No UX work there.
No routing experiments there.
No shell redesign there.
Only critical bug fixes if absolutely unavoidable.

## Rule 2

`GoogleLayout` is the only improvement surface.

All UX work, shell work, parity migration, routing work, polish work happen there only.

## Rule 3

One phase, one intent.

Do not combine:

* load ownership changes
* shell rendering changes
* routing changes
* styling changes

inside one phase unless explicitly planned.

## Rule 4

Legacy stays until parity is proven.

The legacy Google sidebar remains available until the new shell has verified parity for the migrated area.

## Rule 5

Every phase ends with a run-log verification.

No phase is considered complete based on code only.
Completion requires:

* runtime test
* log audit
* visible UI verification

